title: Fresh Herbs
description: Fresh herbs are strong-smelling, flavorful plants that can be added to dishes to make them more flavorful. Herbs include basil, cilantro, garlic, dill, rosemary, oregano and thyme as well as others. Garlic is an herb but is a bulb shape. Fresh herbs are usually green, but some variations can make them different colors.

facility.name: Marjoram
facility.details: Dried marjoram is a popular addition to salad dressings, meat dishes, and preserved meats such as German sausage. Used in both fresh and dried form, marjoram is subtler than its relative oregano and well suited to delicate vegetables, tomato-based dishes, such as tomato sauce and pizza, and poultry seasoning.

facility.name: Mint
facility.details: Eating fresh or dried leaves: Used to treat bad breath. Inhaling essential oils: May improve brain function and cold symptoms. Applying it to the skin: Used to reduce nipple pain from breastfeeding. Taking capsules with food: May help treat IBS and indigestion.

facility.name: Oregano
facility.details: Oregano contains chemicals that might help reduce cough. Oregano also might help with digestion and with fighting against some bacteria and viruses. People use oregano for wound healing, parasite infections, and many other conditions, but there is no good scientific evidence to support these uses.

facility.name: Parsley Continental
facility.details: Continental parsley has a robust flavour. It is very versatile as a salad leaf and as a fresh seasoning. It looks a little like coriander. Use in stocks, sauces, soups, pesto, or add to a rice or pasta dish just before serving.

title: Fresh Vegetables
description: Check the characteristic signs of freshness such as bright, lively color in the vegetable and look to see if the vegetable is crisp and free of soft spots. Vegetables are at their peak during their harvest season, this is also when vegetables are the most affordable to purchase.Quality factors for fruits include the followingâ€” maturity, firmness, the uniformity of size and shape, the absence of defects, skin and flesh color. Many of the same quality factors are described for vegetables, with the addition of texture-related attributes such as turgidity, toughness, and tenderness.
